How customer reviews and ratings work

Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

VINE VOICE
4.0 out of 5 stars Interesting accessory. It's lightweight and fits onto my 10.1" off-brand tablet.
Reviewed in the United States on November 21, 2022
Vine Customer Review of Free Product( What's this? )
Reviewing: "OtterBox Utility Latch Series 7" Black W/Out Accessory Bag (Non-Retail/Ships in Polybag)"

I can't really say that this is, or isn't, what I thought it was when I ordered it - because to be frank, when I ordered it, I wasn't fully sure what it was. I haven't ever used anything like this before, but it looked interesting and possibly useful. I'm sure it has its good uses in some cases, but for my particular tablet needs, not so much.

It did fit my 10.1" off-brand tablet. But to clarify, I don't have any kind of rubber case on the tablet to contend with. The buttons and ports on this tablet seem to clear where the straps hook onto the corners. I can see how it might cause an incompatibility issue with some other tablets, though.

The way this accessory works is that you hook each of the 4 rubber straps over the corners of the tablet. Then you slip either your hand, or a few fingers, through the strap on the back. It's supposed to help keep your tablet secure from falling. BTW, you can also rotate the orientation from portrait to landscape and vice versa.

The corner fastening straps seem to be very secure, so I would say that the tablet isn't likely to come out.

All that said, I'm still not entirely sure how useful this is in many scenarios. When I ordered this, I was thinking it had a kickstand in it (probably got confused by looking at another accessory that was similar). And if it had a kickstand, it would be very useful to me.

But, I'm not sure what kind of apps one would use on a tablet that require only one hand, while the other hand is tucked into a strap on the back - except for perhaps using the tablet to draw with, or to take notes, or orders (for instance, in a restaurant). For those uses, I can definitely see the appeal of this. For my general home tablet use, I prefer to have both hands unfettered and holding onto the tablet with both thumbs free.

It is well-made, as are most (if not all) Otter Box products, but I think it would have been more useful for me if there were some type of kickstand built into it. For that reason, I doubt I will continue using it. I'm glad I could try it out, though

D. Ashley Cohen, Ph.D.
VINE VOICE
4.0 out of 5 stars Does not work with some cases, blocks volume on iPad Air
Reviewed in the United States on November 15, 2022
Vine Customer Review of Free Product( What's this? )
I wasn't confident this would work when I ordered it, but decided to chance that it would fit my iPad Air. Well it sort of does, but won't work with the case I have for it, and even if I used it bare (which I never would), one connector strap covers the upper (raise volume) push button--an unacceptable situation. So, from my perspective, it's an absolute "no go" with respect to the iPad Air, the only platform for me to test it on.

That said, I am able to make some general comments.
1. The material which makes up the backing and the straps is a very "grippy" rubber-like substance. It is soft at first touch, but then you realize it readily picks up any loose items it comes in contact with--i.e., soil, sand, table salt, lint, etc. Even if this unit fit well, I would not use this unit for fear that unseen grit would adhere to the backing, would remain sandwiched between it and the electronic device (e.g., iPad) and would eventually cause scratches to areas where they mate.
2. Trying it for just a short while, I find that I am unable to do any useful work when my hand is in the strap, and am just not comfortable having one hand taken out of action. Sure you can remove your hand, but the action of taking it on and off probably puts the device at more risk than just holding it without the strap.
3. Again, in the short while I was using this unit, I found the hand strap rather tight for my medium size mens hands. I just don't find the ischemia an acceptable trade off for security of grip.
4. I'm more than a little irritated with the way the Warranty information is presented. This is not going to become a Rosetta Stone for future generations--there's no need to supply 47 languages (just kidding, its probably only a couple dozen), though it's irrelevant anyway because they are using gray 2 point type set against a slightly lighter background. Even in bright light and with my most powerful set of reading glasses, I find it fatiguing to attempt to read the information. This is so unecessary and disresptful to the consumer.

In the end, since I am not going to be using this, I'm taking off only one star for the scratch problem and the absurd statement of warranty. Frankly, if I were to be using this device more, I suspect my ranking would go down, rather than up. So, for now, 4 stars.
